    stimulus: 'Economists studying the effects of minimum wage increases have found that employment impacts vary substantially depending on the local labor market context. In labor markets where a single employer or a small number of employers dominate hiring in a particular sector — a structure economists call monopsony — minimum wage increases can raise employment levels by reducing the employer\'s ability to suppress wages below competitive market rates. Researchers argue that this context-dependence means blanket predictions about minimum wage effects are likely to be systematically misleading.\n\nA researcher argues that the traditional economic model predicting that minimum wage increases always reduce employment is insufficient to explain real-world outcomes.',
    question: 'Which finding from an economics study would most directly support the researcher\'s argument?',
